{
  "masechta": "Zevachim",
  "daf": 14,
  "amud": "b",
  "macro_segments": [
    {
      "title": "Introduction and Overview of the Four Avodos and Pigul/Shelo Lishma",
      "display_title": "Four Avodos & Pigul",
      "timestamp": "00:00",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Opening remarks and daf orientation; the four avodos of sacrifice (shechita, kabbalas hadam, holacha, zerika)",
          "display_title": "Opening & Four Avodos",
          "timestamp": "00:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Introduction to piggul and shelo lishma; their effects on olah, chatas, and pesach",
          "display_title": "Piggul & Shelo Lishma",
          "timestamp": "00:41"
        },
        {
          "title": "The debate over whether dipping the finger (tvillas etzba) in the blood of the chatas constitutes an avodah",
          "display_title": "Tvillas Etzba as Avodah",
          "timestamp": "01:05"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Tannaim Debate: Tvillas Etzba in Inner vs. Outer Chatas and the Role of Explicit Scripture",
      "display_title": "Tvillas Etzba Tannaim",
      "timestamp": "03:30",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "The Baraita: one position says tvillas etzba can cause piggul in chatas; another says it cannot",
          "display_title": "Baraita on Tvillas Etzba",
          "timestamp": "03:30"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara reframes: this is a machlokes between Rabbanan and Rabbi Shimon regarding whether holacha counts for piggul purposes",
          "display_title": "Rabbanan vs. R. Shimon",
          "timestamp": "04:35"
        },
        {
          "title": "Discussion of inner vs. outer chatas: inner chatas explicitly mentions dipping in the pasuk; outer chatas only implies it via the word velakach",
          "display_title": "Inner/Outer Chatas",
          "timestamp": "05:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Monkey example: even for outer chatas, re-dipping is required, suggesting holacha-like act is necessary",
          "display_title": "Monkey Example",
          "timestamp": "08:13"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Significance of Explicit Scriptural Mention and Its Bearing on Avodah Status",
      "display_title": "Scripture & Avodah",
      "timestamp": "08:50",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Why the outer chatas, though requiring dipping, is not considered a central avodah: the pasuk does not explicitly say vtaval",
          "display_title": "Why Not Vtaval",
          "timestamp": "08:50"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara's reasoning: since the pasuk does not explicitly label tvillas etzba as required, thought during this act does not invalidate for outer chatas",
          "display_title": "No Explicit = No Piggul",
          "timestamp": "09:02"
        },
        {
          "title": "Summary: inner chatas—tvillas etzba is an avodah affecting piggul; outer chatas—tvillas etzba is necessary but not an avodah for invalidation",
          "display_title": "Inner/Outer Summary",
          "timestamp": "10:00"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Rabbi Shimon's Position on Holacha and Its Application to Inner Chatas",
      "display_title": "R. Shimon & Holacha",
      "timestamp": "11:12",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Shimon's general principle: holacha is an avodah you can avoid, so thought does not invalidate",
          "display_title": "R. Shimon's Principle",
          "timestamp": "11:12"
        },
        {
          "title": "Exception: inner chatas, where holacha must happen (cannot slaughter inside); therefore thought invalidates even for R. Shimon",
          "display_title": "Inner Chatas Exception",
          "timestamp": "11:16"
        },
        {
          "title": "Explanation via Temple layout: shechita must occur outside the ulam and heichal, making holacha necessary",
          "display_title": "Temple Layout Diagram",
          "timestamp": "12:00"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Girsa Challenge: Piggul vs. Shelo Lishma in Inner Chatas and the Kal Vachomer Logic",
      "display_title": "Piggul/Shelo Lishma",
      "timestamp": "13:50",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Objection: R. Shimon says piggul does not apply to inner chatas (not on outer altar); how can shelo lishma invalidate?",
          "display_title": "Piggul Problem",
          "timestamp": "13:50"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rebbi Yosi b'Rebbi Chanina's resolution: R. Shimon only excludes piggul status on the meat (no kares); invalidation of the korban itself remains",
          "display_title": "Piggul on Meat Only",
          "timestamp": "14:51"
        },
        {
          "title": "Kal vachomer: chutz lizmano and chutz limkomo both invalidate, as the pasuk links them",
          "display_title": "Kal Vachomer",
          "timestamp": "16:49"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Exploration of Necessary Holacha: Determining Where Shechita Must Occur and Its Effect on Thought Invalidation",
      "display_title": "Necessary Holacha",
      "timestamp": "23:08",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rava's first position: according to R. Shimon, shechita must occur at the north of the outer altar; necessary holacha is from that point",
          "display_title": "Shechita Location",
          "timestamp": "23:08"
        },
        {
          "title": "Refinement: the space between ulam and mizbeach counts as north; shechita can occur there, reducing necessary holacha to from the ulam door inward",
          "display_title": "North Space",
          "timestamp": "23:40"
        },
        {
          "title": "Alternate view: if heichal and ulam share sanctity, necessary holacha is only from the ulam door outward (through the doorway thickness)",
          "display_title": "Ulam Door Threshold",
          "timestamp": "27:18"
        },
        {
          "title": "Further refinement: if the doorway itself has heichal sanctity, necessary holacha may be only the stretching of the arm to place incense on the floor",
          "display_title": "Arm Stretch Only",
          "timestamp": "29:10"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Question of Whether Holacha Requires Bodily Movement (Holacha Shelo Beregel)",
      "display_title": "Holacha Beregel",
      "timestamp": "31:14",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Introduction: if blood is passed hand-to-hand without walking, does it constitute valid holacha?",
          "display_title": "Hand-to-Hand Transfer",
          "timestamp": "31:14"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Holacha by a Non-Kohen: Correlation with Avodah Status and Sources",
      "display_title": "Non-Kohen Holacha",
      "timestamp": "34:20",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Abaye's question to Rav Chisda: can a non-kohen perform holacha (carrying the blood)?",
          "display_title": "Abaye's Question",
          "timestamp": "34:20"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Chisda's answer via Pesach source: non-kohen brought blood to kohanim for sprinkling",
          "display_title": "Rav Chisda's Source",
          "timestamp": "35:24"
        },
        {
          "title": "Counter-source (Rav Sheshes): explicit Baraita states zar is pasul for holacha",
          "display_title": "Rav Sheshes Counter",
          "timestamp": "36:16"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara resolution: the Pesach narrative describes non-kohen acting as a pedestal/vessel, not performing actual holacha",
          "display_title": "Pedestal Solution",
          "timestamp": "37:16"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabba and Rav Yosef: non-kohen holacha is a machlokes between R. Shimon and Rabbanan based on avodah status of holacha",
          "display_title": "Machlokes R. Shimon",
          "timestamp": "38:31"
        },
        {
          "title": "Abaye challenges the correlation: shechita is not an avodah yet non-kohen cannot do it in para aduma",
          "display_title": "Abaye's Challenge",
          "timestamp": "39:58"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara response: shechita is not an avodah (can be done by non-kohen); but para aduma is outside the korban context",
          "display_title": "Shechita Non-Avodah",
          "timestamp": "40:45"
        },
        {
          "title": "Conclusion via Ulla/R. Elazar: even according to R. Shimon, non-kohen holacha is pasul",
          "display_title": "Holacha Always Pasul",
          "timestamp": "49:21"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Question of Whether Holacha Requires Bodily Movement (Holacha Shelo Beregel) (continued)",
      "display_title": "Holacha Beregel (II)",
      "timestamp": "52:15",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Source 1: wording about sitting and left hand invalidates—suggesting standing movement is required",
          "display_title": "Sitting/Left Hand",
          "timestamp": "52:15"
        },
        {
          "title": "Source 2: Pesach narrative—Israelites slaughter, kohanim catch blood, passed hand-to-hand, then sprinkled",
          "display_title": "Pesach Narrative",
          "timestamp": "53:35"
        },
        {
          "title": "Ambiguity of passing to one who is pasul: must the initial kohen redo it, or can another kohen take from the pasul's hands?",
          "display_title": "Pasul Recipient",
          "timestamp": "55:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Conclusion: the Gemara does not definitively resolve whether holacha requires traversing with the feet (holacha beregel)",
          "display_title": "Unresolved Question",
          "timestamp": "56:22"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
